        <Title>push before introducing third witch</Title>
        <Text>God’s own envoy stepped up to the edge of a barren plateau. Far below her painted toes lay a red rock valley. This valley coursed into a desert, where its dry riverbed choked on sand. The sight of it stirred her memory, for that valley and its river once sustained an idyllic clime. The riverbanks bloomed with wildflowers. The sweet smell excited every little butterfly and bee. Chirping birds hunted those drunken insect swarms, and the meat of those birds fed foxes, and all of them, at different stages of life, from womb to carrion corpse, fed lizards. The meat of the lizards fed larger birds, and on the circle went. Now, that circle was a flat line of compacted sand which never saw rain. The only things which grew were lichens that looked like brown rags. They sustained nothing but themselves as they soaked up the evening mist.
She stepped off the cliff.
Her white robes clung to her body as she fell.
The wind ripped tears from her eyes.
Better for her that she should die instead of be stuck with these memories. Better for her, but only her; for everyone else, she needed to see the day through.
She clenched her fists and swerved out of her fall with the power of flight. She zipped through the red rock valley. She followed its course out into the desert, tracing the sinuous route of the fossilizing river. On any other day, the emptiness here would have made her sick. On this day, the absence of life brought a somber peace, for if the world was alive with creatures, they would see her in this state. It was better that she was alone.
She bit her lip to keep from breaking.
Embarrassed, she wiped her cheek clean from the stain of tears. She slowed down to gather herself, and now she bit her lip in anger, because all those plants and animals were dead, elsewhere they were dying, and she’d thought to pity herself instead of them.
Her selfishness was appalling.
Unconscionable.
What was the stain of her memory compared to the suffering of the littlest creature?
Remembering her purpose, she resumed her flight. Neither guilt nor shame would stop her from reaching the appointed place at the appointed time. She flew across the wasteland, chasing the setting sun. At length, the tip of the sun dipped below the rim of the world and she saw her destination: a wide stone square sitting alone in the middle of desert. 
She picked up speed the swept down, alighting upon the stone square with a whirlwind.
Pellora was already there, sitting on a drop cloth stool. She turned her shaven head to give the envoy a minimal greeting, then returned her sight to the sweep of pink sunset.
Pellora was younger. Her white robes were less carefully arranged, and fashioned as they were from a transparent silk they left nothing to the imagination, even where the material bunched. It was not seductive, and neither was it meant to be. The transparency was meant to draw attention to the falseness of the boundary, as clothes were only an artifice disguising a naked and uncomfortable truth. If Pellora could have managed it, she would turned her skin transparent as well, for in her god’s view, all boundaries, even the body, were false.
 The envoy detested Pellora. Rival was not a strong enough a word. Neither was enemy. Evil would ascribe malice, and that wasn’t quite correct, for Pellora’s fault was ignorance. What but ignorance else could drive that rude smirk? And a bitter ignorance it was. Pellora was near enough to the root of all troubles.
“I’m surprised you are alone.”
“Oh?” Pellora asked. “You were expecting assassins? I’m not always scheming. A little prophylactic murder does give a little high, but all of this is different. We’re working together on this betrayal.” There was an eagerness about her. There was always an eagerness about her, and by the envoy’s judgment, that eagerness was fake.
“Keep your voice low,” the envoy said.
“Why?” Pellora replied, chuckling. “They can’t hear us. They’re too far away. In fact, even if They were close, I doubt it would matter. I doubt any of the gods were ever capable of hearing. Prayers go right through them. You know how they always keep themselves at a distance. I always took it as a sort of divine regality, but lately I’ve begun to wonder.”
The envoy grumbled. Pellora grimaced in turn.
“Oh, please,” Pellora said. “Don’t pretend to fear them. Your god, my god, neither are in control.”
“I know.”
“I know that you know,” Pellora said. “I’m only surprised that you came to me about it.” She stood up and kicked her stool. Instead of clattering onto the stone, it blinked out of existence. “Maybe I shouldn’t be surprised, because you and I are so similar.”
“We are nothing alike.”
“On the other hand,” Pellora continued, “Killing my god is a natural consequence of my philosophy. One might say my god demands it. Your god, however…I didn’t take you for a heretic.”
“Pellora, I will not countenance your foolishness. Not today.”
“You’re not a heretic? Do you have a different definition of the word ‘betrayal’?”
“My god lives only to sustain this world against the likes of you and yours.”
“So, what? You kill Him, and then you kill me, is that it?”
“Yes.”
“You are going to use me to open the door so that you can kill me.”
“I am not a schemer like you, 
“Oh, please. That’s not what’s happening here. You’ve lost faith.”

“I don’t blame you. I have, too. Why would anyone struggle day after day, only to have every victory turned into  What use is a victory if the remnants of those you defeat inevitably find some foothold to nurse their strength, and, in time, start the fight all over again? You crave a battle to end all battles. I crave the same.”
“No,” the envoy said, “You crave the end of all things.”

“How will you do it?” 
Pel sensitive to it. World changign to hear the voice of woman.
“How will I do what?”
“Fulfill our agreement.”
“What agreement? I want to hear you say it.”
“How will you kill Them?”
“Kill who? I aim to kill lots of people.”
“I will not indulge your sadism.”
“Is that where you draw the line? Killing your own god is an odd item to put below it.”
“So long as you kill yours, too.”
“Yes, that is inevitable isn’t it. Both must killed so that we can finally kill each other.”
“How will you do it.”
“Does it matter?”
“Yes.”
“Well it took a lot of thinking. And dreaming.” she said fervently. “I had a dream wherein I discovered the words which could contain Them. I assembled a chorus to chant Their names. It sounds silly, but if you heard Their names repeated, each note entering on the finger, each new voice swelling the chord until the wash of noise did shake the earth…such was the echo in the valleys that one and twenty voices blossomed into twelve and thousands!”
She was speaking now to the sky, to the stars beyond it. There was a younger face beneath her wrinkling years. “It did subdue Them,” she claimed. “For an age of peace, it stilled Their being. Then I woke back up into this nightmare—into the futility of Their illness. I resolved to be done with it. It was then that I realized that there is only. I’ve chosen to delve into the mysteries of the Black.”
“You what!?&quot;
“Oh, please. Don’t act like you didn’t already know the answer. You’ve thought of it, too. Only, you’re too much of a . You absolve your conscious by deferring the indignity to me. Which, I hope you know, makes you worse than me. Not only will their death be on your hands, but so will the stain of shirking responsibility. Well, I won’t let you off so easy. When the gods are all dead, you’ll have no one left to repent to but to yourself, and to me. I will not forgive you for it.”
“I didn’t expect you would.”
“You know, I’ve come to despise you. More than enemies. At this point, I want more than to defeat you. I want to visit you on your death bed to remind you that we all turn to dust, and that despite all your ambitions you will never live to see them through. Despite how special you think you are, all that's left for you is an eternity of loneliness at best, and an eternity of hell at worst. I want you to know that your entire life’s work was a waste, and the only thing you will experience for the relatively short time you have left is the of my triumph over you.”
 I say all this to make sure you understand that, after the deed is done, all our conventions will be cast aside. The next time we meet, it will be death.

“I found a spot of Black free floating out there in the void. I have aimed it at the mountain where They watch.”




