She flew up into the sky. Such was her speed, that her white robes buzzed behind her. She pushed through the thick of the sky to find the uninterrupted night. The stars, in their sparkling multitude, were always . She floated there in the liminal space between the void and the bright earth.

She drifted up against the chunk of Black. It’s enormity humbled her. She’d seen larger stones, but this was of a substance which defied all size comparison. It would seem larger next to objectively larger things. And though it floated freely, it was, somehow, still embedded in the void; its edges extruded out of the black space which was infinitely distant, all to make a jagged body, chaotically pinched, a spiky complex of scar contractures on the skin of night. An ugly wound from an old and ugly injury. With such a substance, size was not a relational thing, but a deep internal feeling; in size, it felt to her like a small city had been glassed into obsidian, then broken, then smushed up into a ball, then hammered into a shape which evoked despair.
The thing turned, slowly, through its tempted orbit. Its fractaled surface multiplied the points of stars. It turned, slowly, to reveal a flat, cylindrical head that would strike the world like a hammer.
And what was the world, now?
From this height, she could see it all. She could remember it all.
That once green paradise was crusted over with history. Grim monuments to abandoned civilizations trimmed every river bend—gray lesions on the skin of a dying world. Great pastures which once nursed untold scores of life had been ruined by herds of cattle. The waters were all drunk dry. Bare mountains rumpled up the of tectonic plates, old wounds. It had been a slow, slow death. Most of the colors dipped into gray. And there amongst it was her god. Blinding white, and sparkling, He looked like a fallen star twinkling atop the tallest peak of the Goree mountains. 
Of creation.
Childhood. The birth of language and its quick evolution. The first kingship. The first sailing ship. The first minted silver coin and the first imitation of it; a thin bit of copper washed in pewter. The urge to horde. The night she gained the sight. Anatomy lessons with the flayed. The long charter of the fleshcraft guild. The temptations of priests. The origins of debt. The operations of war. The shock of famine. King Sixa’s plan to pot the desert with wells. The explosion of Mount Volgi which poisoned half the continent. The Folzeek revolution and the splintering of the zagoqa tribes. The beginning of table manners. The deep hunger driving demons through the tunnels of the world. Greed chewing at every city’s roots. Salosa’s denuded self becoming a goddess. All these memories were condensed into one big emotion, and the tears were boiled away when the meteor set fire in the atmosphere. When it smashed through the clouds she sank into more primitive categories of feeling.
Fear of her father.
Anger at injustice.
And finally, guilt.
Each wound in her life now seemed like an accident, arbitrary, for how far could her god have seen when He was weaving her fate? He could not see this massive spot of Black coming to end Him.

The Black fell upon Him.
The collision shook the earth.
The soundlessness of space muted her sigh of awe.
for at A round shockwave spread, swept away the god cloud like it was nothing, flattened the armies battling below it, then went out to the sea to steam the surface of the waters, stir up the magnificent phytoplankton blooms, thousands of miles long, glowing prussian-blue in whirling gyres. The shock went on to circle the globe, sweeping clouds thin, dragging a shade of dust behind it.
And so the stage was set for the beginning of the end. It was her against the shadow. The gods were dead. One of them would finally win.</Text>
